snippet.textDisplay: From a young age, I have always loved cooking and making meals for everyone. I come from a family that will try and feed anyone one within a 6 mile radius and cook in large batches. So by the time I went off to college, I had a good grasp on the basics. One thing this time taught me that has stayed with me through my adult life, is the skill of making wholesome food out of scant ingredients. Being a very poor college kid trying to hold down 3 jobs and full time study, I mastered this out of necessity. We’d pool cash and I was the one who did the cooking and food shop but we always ate fairly well. This video is such a great representation of what I’m sure a few of us did back then. Sometimes the last thing on your mind at that age is to fuss around the kitchen but it’s worth it. I think it helped me with my studies and kept me healthy through what is normally one of the most stressful times in a young person’s life. Best of luck to anyone out there watching this and making these recipes!

snippet.textDisplay:
For the pasta, after you've added the pasta water, remove pan from heat then do the following:

Crack an egg into a bowl, along with a load of parmesan cheese and ground black pepper. Whisk together then pour onto the pasta and stir. You'll have yourself a pasta carbonara. Add chopped bacon as well. Chili flakes aren't technically supposed to be in it but I'm not Italian so I don't give a shit.
